solution:
Starred equation environments suppress equation numbering. To display equation numbers, remove the star from the environment:
- Change \begin{align*} to \begin{align} and \end{align*} to \end{align}
- Change \begin{equation*} to \begin{equation} and \end{equation*} to \end{equation}
If the equation number is not required, keep the starred environment as is.

Do not use \displaystyle at the beginning of an equation. Example to avoid:
\displaystyle \begin{equation} .... \end{equation}

The \displaystyle command should be used selectively within the equation — for example, before characters like \sigma or \sum — not at the equation level. Using it at the start of the equation environment has no effect on font or style.

The {rc} parameter is not valid for the gather environment. Remove it.

Incorrect:
\begin{gather}{rc}
  equation content
\end{gather}

Corrected:
\begin{gather}
  equation content
\end{gather}

The gather environment does not accept parameters — remove any text between \begin{gather} and the first equation line.

Use the align environment instead of equation+split for multiline equations. The align environment handles multiple lines better, keeps spacing clean, and avoids label merging.

Instead of:
\begin{equation}\begin{split}... \\ ...\end{split}\end{equation}

Use:
\begin{align}... \\ ...\end{align}

For custom numbering:
\begin{align}\tag{2.28}\begin{split}... \\ ...\end{split}\end{align}

Use \notag to skip numbers on specific lines.

Replace \sum_\limits{...} with \displaystyle \sum_{...} inside the cases environment.

Incorrect (causes rendering error):
\sum_\limits{i=0}^{N}k_{\textrm{off}}C_{i}

Corrected:
\displaystyle \sum_{i=0}^{N}k_{\textrm{off}}C_{i}

Remove all instances of \limits inside \begin{cases} and replace with the \displaystyle prefix before the sum/product operator.

Replace deprecated commands with modern equivalents:

Bold text:
  Avoid: {\bf text} or \bf text
  Use: \textbf{text}

Italic text:
  Avoid: {\it text} or \it text
  Use: \textit{text}

Roman font:
  Avoid: {\rm text} or \rm text
  Use: \textrm{text}

Sans-serif: use \textsf{text}
Typewriter/monospace: use \texttt{text}
